^b@2^*bQ.^*n   What is a     ^*bDouble Dummy Solver^*n      (DDS) ? 

|cp|8|at|^*bA.^*n|cp||at|   It is a piece of code that takes a deal and a contract denomination e.g. "hearts" and by looking at all four hands (hence the expression Double Dummy) can check all the combinations of plays and so work out (assuming best play) the most tricks that each side can make.

When you are  ^*bInside a Deal^*n  you should see a the letters   ^*bDDS^*n   near the top of the right hand column.  When the DDS is turned on you will see green and amber ovals by all playable cards.  The number inside each oval shows (assuming best play from both sides) the total tricks that can be made if that card is played.  Green ovals mark play as 'best'.   When reviewing, the card that will be played 'next', is also marked with a coloured circle.

|fp|3|cp|2|at|Hint|fp||at|^*b   in Review use the Fwd Single arrow button THEN use the mouse wheel to see each card played.|cp||at|^*n

^*baaBridge^*n can also use Bo's DDS to check all the autoplays that the "dumb aaBridge auto-player" suggests.   If the DDS says that a particular play will cost a trick then a DDS suggested play, is used instead.


^b@2^*bQ.^*n   How do I tell if the  ^*bDouble Dummy Solver^*n  is Available ?

|cp|8|at|^*bA.^*n|cp||at|   Select  ^*bAutoPlay^*n  (top of the Right panel).  Look just under the AutoPlay (green) title, top of box.   If you can see |cp|5|at|^*b DDS Available ^*n|cp||at| then the check box below controls whether or not it is in use.   If you see |cp|9|at|^*b DDS NOT Available ^*n|cp||at| then you are out of luck.  It should be "available" on nearly all systems including   Windows, Mac and some Linux.|

